      <div xml:id="NA37-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiviṭai vaittup piriviṉkaṇ tōḻi (ET: piriyak karutum talaimakaṟkut tōḻi) colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidant said in the time of separation after the time for marriage had been set.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA37">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            piṇaṅkaril vāṭiya paḻaviṟa ṉaṉantalai</l>
<l>            yuṇaṅkū ṇāyat tōrāṉ ṟeṇmaṇi</l>
<l>            paiya vicaikku mattam vaiyeyiṟ</l>
<l>            ṟivaḷoṭuñ celiṉō naṉṟē kuvaḷai</l>
<l>            nīrcūḻ māmala raṉṉa kaṇṇaḻak </l>
<l>            kalaiyoḻi piṇaiyiṟ kalaṅki māṟi</l>
<l>            yaṉpili rakaṟi rāyi ṉeṉpara</l>
<l>            mākuva taṉṟiva ḷavala nākat</l>
<l>            taṇaṅkuṭai yaruntalai yuṭali valaṉēr</l>
<l>            pārkali nallēṟu tiritaruṅ </l>
<l>            kārcey mālai varūum poḻutē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>It [would be] good if you go with her</l>
<l rend="indent">of sharp teeth on the road,</l>
<l rend="indent4">where the clear bell on the one cow</l>
<l rend="indent2">from the herd gently sounds, [eating] dry food</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the vast area of the old victory(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paḻa viṟal</term> is strange here, and watering it down to "old beauty" (thus T.V.G.) is no more than a makeshift solution.</note> where the</l>
<l rend="indent4">intertwined thicket has faded.</l>
<l>If you are devoid of love [and] leave [her],</l>
<l rend="indent2">being changed, upsetting [her]<note place="foot">Here it appears necessary to take <term xml:lang="ta">kalaṅkutal</term> in a transitive sense, for which one would want parallels. </note> like the doe left by the stag,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that [her] eyes cry, like big waterlily blossoms surrounded by water,</l>
<l>it won't be in my capacity [to bear] her distress,</l>
<l rend="indent">– at a time<note place="foot">Here we have the real kind of circular construction: <term xml:lang="ta">poḻutu</term> will go equally well with both preceding sentences.</note> when evening comes, making(?) the rainy season,</l>
<l rend="indent">when a loudly clamouring good [thunder]clap, risen with strength,</l>
<l rend="indent">attacks the tormentd, difficult head of a snake [and] twists [it].</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="8-11B"><note place="foot">It is, however, equally well possible to read <term xml:lang="ta">ivaḷ avalam</term> as the subject of a nominal clause with <term xml:lang="ta">poḻutu</term> as a predicate noun.</note>>
<l>Her distress</l>
<l>[is] the time when evening comes….</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
